1. Introduction to Ansible
What is Ansible?
Ansible is a radically simple, open-source IT automation tool (agentless configuration management, application deployment, and orchestration). It uses SSH (no agents required on remote hosts) and describes automation in plain English-like YAML.
Key Benefits:

Free & open-source
Easy to learn (no heavy coding)
Idempotent (safe to run multiple times — only makes changes if needed)
Modular and reusable
Works for cloud, networks, servers, security, etc.

Use Cases:

Provisioning servers
Deploying web servers (e.g., Nginx/Apache)
Configuration management
Application deployment
Orchestration
Cloud automation

Architecture (High-level):

Control Node (where Ansible is installed — usually Linux)
Managed Nodes (remote hosts — no Ansible installed)
Communication via SSH + Python (modules executed remotely)
Inventory defines targets
Playbooks define what to do

Installation (on Control Node - Ubuntu/Debian example):
Bashsudo apt update
sudo apt install ansible -y
ansible --version
